			    <h1>Herbalist</h1>

			    <p>Traditional medicine has been a part of Chinese culture for thousands of years.   Some Chinese-Americans still use traditional medicine to a variety of degrees.  In Kent Young Health Products, customers can buy a wide range of herbs imported from China to treat their health issues.  From basic ailments like the common cold or a traditional diagnosis like a “Yin-deficiency”, customers can discuss symptoms and receive the best treatment for them.  The treatments can come in the form of pre-packaged supplements and loose herbs depending on customer preference.  Loose herbs are frequently used in more traditional treatments, like brewing teas at home.  Visitors can find a wide variety of supplements and teas throughout the store.</p>

			    <p>Some Traditional Chinese Medicine stores also provide acupuncture and other alternative-medicine services.  While treatments like acupuncture were originally part of Traditional Chinese Medicine, westerners have begun to embrace them as well.  Dr. Yang is the owner of Kent Young Health Products, Inc. He studied at the Zhong Shan Medical College in Guangzhou, China.</p>
			    <img src="/images/locations/medicine.jpg" class="img-fluid rounded" alt="Image of various boxes of herbal remedies">
                            <p>At first, he studied Western medicine, then he studied some acupuncture and eventually Traditional Chinese Medicine.In Chicago it is required to be licensed in order to practice acupuncture, but it there is no licensing structure for practicing herbal medicine. California requires an herbal medicine license, as well as New York. In Chicago, however, the herbs are treated as if they were food, not medicine. Thus, anyone could sell the herbs, even if they do not have a degree or experience.Dr. Yang notes that some herbs that are legal in some states are illegal in others. For example, ma huang, which has long been a treatment for asthma, is illegal in Chicago, but may be legal in Indiana. Like any medicine, herbs in the wrong concentration or mixed incorrectly can have adverse effects. Dr. Yang walked us through the entire process of how one comes in with a problem and leaves with an herbal remedy. As someone comes toward his desk, he starts by observing them. He looks at the way they walk, coloration of their skin, and their eyes. He listens to the way they talk and takes note of any problems. Then he takes their pulse and listens to what they feel their problems are.</p>
